{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Go to git-scm.com in your web browser. This is the official Git website where you'll download the installer.",
      "title": "Open the Git Website"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the large download button on the homepage. The site automatically detects your operating system and offers the correct version.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Find the downloaded file in your Downloads folder and double-click it to start the installation wizard.",
      "title": "Run the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click through the installation screens, accepting the default options. These defaults work well for most users. Click Next on each screen until you reach Install.",
      "title": "Accept Default Settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the Install button and wait for the progress bar to complete. This usually takes 1-2 minutes.",
      "title": "Complete Installation"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, open Command Prompt or PowerShell from the Start menu. On Mac, open Terminal from Applications > Utilities.",
      "title": "Open Your Terminal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see a version number like \"git version 2.43.0\" confirming Git is installed correctly.",
      "title": "Verify Installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Drive to a flat, stable surface away from traffic. Turn on your hazard lights and engage the parking brake. Place wheel wedges behind the tires to prevent rolling.",
      "title": "Park Safely and Secure the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your trunk and locate the spare tire, jack, and lug wrench. Place them on the ground near the flat tire. Check that the jack is not damaged or bent.",
      "title": "Gather Your Equipment"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use the flat end of your lug wrench or a flathead screwdriver to pry off the hubcap or wheel cover. Set it aside face-up to hold the lug nuts later.",
      "title": "Remove the Hubcap"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn each lug nut counterclockwise one full turn using the lug wrench. Don't remove them completely yet—just break the resistance while the tire is still on the ground for stability.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check your owner's manual for the exact jack placement point near the flat tire. It's usually a reinforced metal area on the frame behind the front wheel or ahead of the rear wheel.",
      "title": "Find the Jack Point"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slide the jack under the vehicle at the designated jack point. Ensure the jack head contacts the frame squarely, not at an angle. The jack should sit firmly on level ground.",
      "title": "Position the Jack"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise or pump it to raise the vehicle. Lift until the flat tire is about 6 inches off the ground. The tire should spin freely without touching the surface.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now remove the lug nuts completely by turning counterclockwise. Place them in the hubcap or your pocket so they don't roll away. Keep track of all nuts—you need every one.",
      "title": "Fully Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire by the treads and pull it straight toward you. It may be stuck—wiggle it side to side if needed. Once free, lay it flat on the ground away from the road.",
      "title": "Pull Off the Flat Tire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at the wheel hub where the tire was mounted. It should be clean with visible bolt studs. The vehicle should remain stable on the jack. You're now ready to mount the spare.",
      "title": "Verify Successful Removal"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Weigh out 30 grams of coffee beans (about 4 tablespoons) for a standard 4-cup French press. Adjust by 7-8 grams per cup if making more or less.",
      "title": "Measure Your Coffee Beans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grind the beans to a coarse consistency, similar to sea salt. Too fine will make bitter coffee and clog the filter. You should see distinct particles, not powder.",
      "title": "Grind to Coarse Texture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bring fresh, filtered water to a boil, then let it cool for 30-60 seconds. Target temperature is 195-205°F (90-96°C). Boiling water will scorch the grounds.",
      "title": "Heat Your Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove the plunger and lid from your French press. Add the ground coffee directly into the empty glass carafe. Shake gently to level the bed of grounds.",
      "title": "Add Grounds to Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Start a timer and pour hot water over the grounds until the carafe is about one-third full. This allows the coffee to \"bloom\" and release gases.",
      "title": "Pour Water to Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Wait 30 seconds while the coffee blooms. You should see the grounds puff up and bubble slightly as CO2 escapes. This ensures even extraction.",
      "title": "Wait for Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the remaining hot water slowly over the grounds until you reach the top line of the carafe. Use a total water-to-coffee ratio of about 500ml to 30g.",
      "title": "Fill the Carafe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on top with the plunger pulled all the way up. This traps heat inside. Don't press down yet—the coffee needs to steep.",
      "title": "Place Lid Without Pressing"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the coffee steep undisturbed for exactly 4 minutes. Set a timer. Shorter times produce weak coffee; longer times create bitter, over-extracted flavors.",
      "title": "Steep for 4 Minutes"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer ends, grip the handle firmly with one hand and press the plunger down slowly and steadily. Apply even pressure for 15-20 seconds until fully depressed.",
      "title": "Press the Plunger Down"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee immediately into your cups. Don't let it sit in the French press—the grounds continue extracting and will make the remaining coffee bitter.",
      "title": "Pour and Serve Immediately"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Select a spot in your garden that receives at least 6-8 hours of direct sunlight daily. Mark out an area approximately 3 feet wide by the length you need for your tomato plants.",
      "title": "Choose Your Planting Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden fork or tiller to break up the soil to a depth of 12-14 inches. Work across the entire bed area, turning the soil over completely. Compacted soil should become loose and crumbly.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil Deeply"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pick out any rocks, roots, weeds, and debris as you work through the soil. Shake loose soil from weed roots before discarding. A clean bed prevents competition for nutrients.",
      "title": "Remove Debris and Weeds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread 2-3 inches of aged compost or well-rotted manure across the entire bed surface. This adds essential nutrients and improves soil structure for tomato roots.",
      "title": "Add Organic Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scatter balanced granular fertilizer (10-10-10) over the compost at the rate listed on the package, typically about 2 pounds per 100 square feet. Avoid piling fertilizer in one spot.",
      "title": "Apply Balanced Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "If your soil is heavy clay, add a 1-inch layer of perlite or coarse sand. For sandy soil, add extra compost. This improves drainage and water retention respectively.",
      "title": "Improve Soil Texture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your garden fork to mix all amendments thoroughly into the loosened soil. Work the entire depth, blending compost, fertilizer, and amendments evenly throughout.",
      "title": "Mix Amendments into Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drag a garden rake across the surface to break up clumps and create a smooth, level planting surface. Remove any remaining debris that surfaces during raking.",
      "title": "Rake the Bed Smooth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Soak the prepared bed deeply with a hose or sprinkler until water penetrates 6 inches down. Check by pushing a finger into the soil. Let the bed rest for 24-48 hours before planting.",
      "title": "Water the Bed Thoroughly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your soil is ready when it holds together slightly when squeezed but crumbles easily when poked. It should smell earthy and look dark brown. You're now ready to plant tomatoes.",
      "title": "Confirm Soil Is Ready"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Collect your fabric (1 yard of cotton), fabric scissors, measuring tape, straight pins, fabric marker, and a large flat surface like a table or clean floor.",
      "title": "Gather Your Materials"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the fabric flat on your work surface with the printed or \"right\" side facing down. Smooth out any wrinkles with your hands. The fabric should lie completely flat.",
      "title": "Lay Fabric Wrong Side Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "For a standard pillowcase, use your measuring tape and fabric marker to mark a rectangle 27 inches wide by 41 inches long. Make small marks at each corner point.",
      "title": "Mark Your Dimensions"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using a ruler or straight edge, connect your corner marks with the fabric marker to create straight cutting lines. Press firmly so the lines are visible but not too thick.",
      "title": "Draw Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place straight pins along the inside of your marked lines, spacing them about 4 inches apart. The pins keep the fabric from shifting while you cut.",
      "title": "Pin Along the Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold your fabric scissors at a slight angle and cut along the marked line in long, smooth strokes. Don't lift the bottom blade off the table. Short choppy cuts create uneven edges.",
      "title": "Cut the First Long Edge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the fabric or move yourself to the next side. Continue cutting along the marked line using the same long, smooth strokes. Keep the fabric flat as you work.",
      "title": "Cut the Short Edge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cut the remaining two sides the same way. Remove pins as you reach them. You should now have a clean 27\" x 41\" rectangle of fabric.",
      "title": "Complete the Rectangle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your measuring tape to verify all four sides. Width should be 27 inches and length 41 inches. If edges are uneven, trim small amounts to straighten them.",
      "title": "Check Your Measurements"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your cut fabric piece should have straight edges and square corners. Fold it in half to confirm both halves match evenly. Set aside for sewing.",
      "title": "Verify Your Cut Piece"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Download a free guitar tuner app like GuitarTuna or Fender Tune on your phone. Open the app and allow microphone access when prompted.",
      "title": "Install a Tuner App"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sit in a quiet room and hold your guitar in playing position. Place your phone nearby where it can clearly hear the strings. Background noise will confuse the tuner.",
      "title": "Position Your Guitar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string (closest to your face). This is the 6th string, which should be tuned to E. The tuner will show what note it detects.",
      "title": "Pluck the 6th String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Watch the tuner display. If the needle points left or shows \"flat,\" the string is too loose. If it points right or shows \"sharp,\" the string is too tight.",
      "title": "Read the Tuner Display"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the tuning peg for the 6th string slowly while plucking. Turn toward you to tighten (raise pitch) or away to loosen (lower pitch). Stop when the tuner shows E and the needle centers.",
      "title": "Adjust the 6th String to E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Move to the 5th string (next one down). Pluck it and adjust the tuning peg until your tuner shows A and the needle is centered.",
      "title": "Tune the 5th String to A"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string and turn its tuning peg until the tuner displays D with a centered needle.",
      "title": "Tune the 4th String to D"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string and adjust until the tuner shows G centered.",
      "title": "Tune the 3rd String to G"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string and tune it to B. This string is thinner, so make smaller adjustments to avoid over-tightening.",
      "title": "Tune the 2nd String to B"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 1st string (thinnest, furthest from your face) and tune it to E. This is a higher E than the 6th string.",
      "title": "Tune the 1st String to E"
    },
    {
      "text": "Play through all strings from 6th to 1st: E-A-D-G-B-E. Use the memory trick \"Eddie Ate Dynamite Good Bye Eddie\" to remember the order.",
      "title": "Verify String Order"
    },
    {
      "text": "Go back and check each string one more time. Tuning one string can slightly affect the others. Make small adjustments until all six strings show centered on the tuner.",
      "title": "Double-Check All Strings"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn your camera's mode dial to M (Manual) mode. This gives you full control over ISO, aperture, and shutter speed settings.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Point your camera at the scene you want to photograph. Look through the viewfinder or at the LCD screen to see the current exposure.",
      "title": "Frame Your Scene"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the exposure meter in your viewfinder or LCD. It's a scale with marks from -3 to +3. The indicator shows if your image will be underexposed (-), overexposed (+), or properly exposed (center).",
      "title": "Find the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the ISO button (or enter the ISO menu) and select ISO 100 for bright outdoor scenes, ISO 400-800 for shade or indoors, or ISO 1600+ for low light. Lower numbers mean less noise.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the aperture dial to choose your f-number. Use f/2.8-f/4 for blurry backgrounds, f/8-f/11 for landscapes. Smaller numbers let in more light.",
      "title": "Choose Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the shutter speed dial while watching the exposure meter. Adjust until the indicator moves to the center (0). For handheld shots, keep shutter speed faster than 1/60th second.",
      "title": "Adjust Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a test shot and review it on your LCD. Use the histogram display if available—the graph should peak in the middle without touching the edges.",
      "title": "Take a Test Photo"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is too dark, either lower the f-number, slow the shutter speed, or increase ISO. If too bright, do the opposite. Retake until the exposure looks correct.",
      "title": "Fine-Tune Your Settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once your exposure looks good on screen and the histogram is balanced, you've successfully set manual exposure. Continue shooting with these settings while light conditions remain similar.",
      "title": "Confirm Proper Exposure"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, toes pointing slightly outward at about 15-30 degrees. Your weight should be evenly distributed across both feet.",
      "title": "Position Your Feet"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extend both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height. This counterbalance helps maintain stability as you descend. Keep your palms facing down.",
      "title": "Extend Your Arms Forward"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull your shoulders back and down, away from your ears. Lift your chest slightly and engage your core by bracing your abdominals as if preparing for a light punch.",
      "title": "Engage Your Core and Chest"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pick a spot on the wall at eye level and keep your gaze fixed there throughout the movement. This helps maintain a neutral spine and prevents rounding forward.",
      "title": "Fix Your Gaze Ahead"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips back first, as if sitting into a chair behind you. Your knees will naturally begin to bend as your hips move backward.",
      "title": "Initiate the Hip Hinge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue lowering until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor. Your knees should track over your toes, not caving inward. Your heels stay flat on the ground.",
      "title": "Lower to Parallel"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the bottom position, check: chest is up, back is straight, knees are over toes, heels are down. If your heels lift or back rounds, only go as deep as you can with good form.",
      "title": "Check Your Bottom Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drive through your heels and midfoot to stand back up. Squeeze your glutes at the top and fully extend your hips. Avoid locking your knees aggressively.",
      "title": "Drive Up Through Your Heels"
    },
    {
      "text": "Perform 5 slow squats, taking 3 seconds to lower and 2 seconds to rise. Focus on maintaining form at each checkpoint. Rest briefly and repeat for another set of 5.",
      "title": "Practice Controlled Repetitions"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe 500g de farinha de trigo, 10g de sal, 10g de fermento biológico seco, 300ml de água morna (cerca de 37°C) e 30ml de azeite. Água muito quente mata o fermento.",
      "title": "Reúna os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture a água morna com o fermento e 1 colher de chá de açúcar. Mexa delicadamente e deixe descansar por 10 minutos. A mistura deve formar espuma na superfície.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Verifique se há uma camada de espuma sobre a água. Se não houver espuma após 10 minutos, o fermento está velho ou a água estava muito quente. Descarte e recomece com fermento novo.",
      "title": "Confirme a ativação"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, coloque a farinha e faça um buraco no centro. Adicione o sal nas bordas da farinha, longe do centro onde irá o fermento ativado.",
      "title": "Prepare a farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje o fermento ativado no centro da farinha. Adicione o azeite por cima. Comece a misturar do centro para as bordas usando uma colher de pau ou espátula.",
      "title": "Misture os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue misturando até formar uma massa grudenta que se solta das laterais da tigela. Se estiver muito seca, adicione água aos poucos. Se muito grudenta, adicione farinha.",
      "title": "Incorpore tudo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polvilhe farinha em uma superfície limpa e lisa. Transfira a massa da tigela para essa superfície. Mantenha um pouco de farinha por perto para usar durante a sova.",
      "title": "Prepare a bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com a palma da mão, empurre a massa para frente, esticando-a. Use movimentos firmes mas não agressivos. A massa vai resistir no início, isso é normal.",
      "title": "Comece a sovar"
    },
    {
      "text": "Após esticar, dobre a massa ao meio trazendo a parte de cima para baixo. Gire a massa 90 graus. Repita o movimento de empurrar, dobrar e girar.",
      "title": "Dobre e gire"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue sovando por 8 a 10 minutos sem parar. Se a massa grudar demais nas mãos, polvilhe um pouco de farinha. Evite adicionar farinha em excesso.",
      "title": "Mantenha o ritmo"
    },
    {
      "text": "A massa está pronta quando ficar lisa, elástica e não grudar nas mãos. Faça o teste: estique um pedaço pequeno. Se formar uma membrana fina sem rasgar, a sova está completa.",
      "title": "Teste a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola, colocando as dobras para baixo. A superfície deve ficar lisa e uniforme. Coloque em uma tigela levemente untada com azeite.",
      "title": "Forme uma bola"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cubra a tigela com plástico filme ou um pano úmido limpo. A cobertura deve ficar bem vedada para manter a umidade e permitir que a massa cresça adequadamente.",
      "title": "Cubra a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Deixe a massa descansar em local morno por 1 hora ou até dobrar de tamanho. Um forno desligado com a luz acesa é um ótimo local. A massa está pronta para a próxima etapa.",
      "title": "Deixe descansar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Busca la llave de paso debajo del lavabo o fregadero. Gírala en sentido horario hasta que no pueda girar más. Si no hay llave local, cierra la llave general de la casa.",
      "title": "Cierra el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre el grifo para liberar el agua restante en las tuberías. Deja que drene completamente. Esto también confirma que el agua está cortada correctamente.",
      "title": "Vacía la presión del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un tapón o trapo en el desagüe del lavabo. Esto evita que tornillos pequeños o piezas caigan accidentalmente por el drenaje durante la reparación.",
      "title": "Tapa el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca una tapa decorativa en la manija del grifo. Usa un destornillador plano para hacer palanca y retirarla. Debajo encontrarás un tornillo de sujeción.",
      "title": "Retira la tapa de la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa un destornillador Phillips o Allen según el tipo de tornillo. Gíralo en sentido antihorario hasta sacarlo completamente. Guárdalo en un lugar seguro.",
      "title": "Quita el tornillo de la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Tira de la manija hacia arriba con firmeza. Si está atascada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado mientras jalas. En grifos antiguos puede requerir algo de fuerza.",
      "title": "Extrae la manija del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Usa una llave ajustable para aflojar la tuerca hexagonal que sujeta el cartucho o vástago. Gira en sentido antihorario. Protege el acabado envolviendo la tuerca con cinta.",
      "title": "Afloja la tuerca de retención"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extrae el cartucho, vástago o disco del interior del grifo. Observa su orientación para instalarlo igual después. Colócalo sobre una toalla limpia.",
      "title": "Saca el cartucho o vástago"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca empaques de goma, arandelas o juntas tóricas en el vástago y dentro del cuerpo del grifo. Las piezas desgastadas se ven aplastadas, agrietadas o endurecidas.",
      "title": "Inspecciona las piezas internas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lleva las piezas dañadas a la ferretería para encontrar repuestos exactos. Si el cartucho está muy desgastado, cómpralo completo. Anota la marca y modelo del grifo.",
      "title": "Consigue los repuestos correctos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aplica una capa fina de grasa de silicona para plomería en las nuevas juntas tóricas y empaques. Esto facilita la instalación y mejora el sellado.",
      "title": "Lubrica las piezas nuevas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca los nuevos empaques y juntas en su posición original. Si reemplazas el cartucho completo, insértalo respetando la orientación que anotaste antes.",
      "title": "Instala los repuestos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Enrosca la tuerca de retención en sentido horario. Aprieta firmemente con la llave ajustable, pero sin excederte para no dañar las roscas o el acabado.",
      "title": "Ajusta la tuerca de retención"
    },
    {
      "text": "Desliza la manija sobre el vástago o cartucho. Inserta y aprieta el tornillo de sujeción. Coloca la tapa decorativa presionándola hasta que encaje.",
      "title": "Reinstala la manija"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira la llave de paso en sentido antihorario para restaurar el flujo de agua. Hazlo lentamente para evitar golpes de presión en las tuberías.",
      "title": "Abre el suministro de agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Abre y cierra el grifo varias veces. Observa durante dos minutos si hay goteos en la base, manija o pico. Un grifo bien reparado no debe soltar ni una gota al cerrarse.",
      "title": "Verifica que no haya fugas"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Look at the top menu bar of your word processor and click on \"File\". A dropdown menu will appear with various options.",
      "title": "Click the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the dropdown menu, click \"Save As\" to open the save dialog. This lets you choose where to save your file and what to name it.",
      "title": "Select Save As"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the save dialog, use the folder navigation on the left to select where you want to store your document, like Documents or Desktop.",
      "title": "Choose a Save Location"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click in the \"File name\" field and type a descriptive name for your document. Use something you'll remember, like \"Meeting Notes\" or \"Project Report\".",
      "title": "Enter a File Name"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the \"Save\" button in the bottom right of the dialog. The window will close and your file name will appear in the title bar at the top.",
      "title": "Click Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "Check the title bar at the top of your window. It should now display your document's name instead of \"Untitled\" or \"Document 1\". This confirms your file is saved.",
      "title": "Verify the Save"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Lay the motherboard on its box or an anti-static surface. Locate the CPU socket — it has a metal retention arm on one side.",
      "title": "Prepare the Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lift the CPU socket's metal retention arm and remove the plastic protective cover. Keep the cover in case you need it for warranty returns later.",
      "title": "Open the CPU Socket"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold the CPU by its edges. Match the golden triangle on the CPU corner with the triangle on the socket. Gently lower the CPU into place — it should drop in without force.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lower the retention arm back down until it clicks securely. The CPU is now locked in place. You should feel firm resistance as the arm latches.",
      "title": "Secure the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Apply a pea-sized dot of thermal paste to the center of the CPU. Skip this if your cooler has pre-applied paste (check the bottom of the cooler).",
